{
  "masechta": "Eruvin",
  "daf": 7,
  "amud": "b",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Introduction to Eruv Requirements and the Case of Bent Alleyways (Mavoi Akum)",
      "display_title": "Eruv Basics & Mavoi",
      "timestamp": "00:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Opening remarks: the fundamental challenge of creating an eruv in reshus harabim",
          "display_title": "Eruv Challenge",
          "timestamp": "00:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Definition of mavoi mefulash and the debate between Rav and Shmuel on whether tzurat hapetach or a door is required",
          "display_title": "Tzurat Hapetach vs Door",
          "timestamp": "01:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "The case of the bent alleyway (mavoi akum) in Nehardea and the application of both stringencies",
          "display_title": "Mavoi Akum Case",
          "timestamp": "03:20"
        },
        {
          "title": "Explanation of Rav's position treating a bent alleyway as straight (torato kemufalash)",
          "display_title": "Rav's Position",
          "timestamp": "05:08"
        },
        {
          "title": "How both stringencies of Rav and Shmuel combine to require a door in the mavoi akum case",
          "display_title": "Both Stringencies",
          "timestamp": "07:12"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Digression on Cherry-Picking Stringencies and Leniencies Between Beit Shammai and Beit Hillel",
      "display_title": "Stringencies Debate",
      "timestamp": "09:34",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Question: do we really combine two separate chumrot that neither side would individually hold?",
          "display_title": "Two Chumrot?",
          "timestamp": "09:34"
        },
        {
          "title": "Citation of brayta on ruling like Beit Hillel versus choosing either position",
          "display_title": "Beit Hillel Rule",
          "timestamp": "10:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "Problem of cherry-picking kulos or chumrot: the rasha (wicked person) who picks leniencies from both sides",
          "display_title": "Cherry-Picking Issue",
          "timestamp": "10:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "The corresponding fool who adopts all chumrot from both sides without consistency",
          "display_title": "Inconsistent Chumrot",
          "timestamp": "11:08"
        },
        {
          "title": "Requirement to choose consistently one school's positions: either Beit Shammai's or Beit Hillel's kulos and chumrot",
          "display_title": "Consistent Choice",
          "timestamp": "11:32"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Resolution: The Bat Kol of Beit Hillel and Beit Shammai and Exceptions via Rabbi Yehoshua",
      "display_title": "Bat Kol & Exceptions",
      "timestamp": "11:50",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Internal contradiction in the brayta: first says we rule like Beit Hillel, then allows ruling like Beit Shammai",
          "display_title": "Internal Contradiction",
          "timestamp": "11:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "Resolution: the brayta reflects two time periods—before and after the bat kol established Beit Hillel as the halacha",
          "display_title": "Before/After Bat Kol",
          "timestamp": "12:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "The story of the heavenly voice (bat kol) declaring we rule like Beit Hillel and Rabbi Yehoshua's response that we ignore bat kol",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yehoshua's Stand",
          "timestamp": "12:35"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tosafot's explanation: the bat kol only decides matters where we lack an established process; once process is known, the bat kol is irrelevant",
          "display_title": "Tosafot's Logic",
          "timestamp": "14:23"
        },
        {
          "title": "Alternative reading: the brayta applies only to analogous debates similar to Beit Shammai and Beit Hillel, where one must pick one school consistently",
          "display_title": "Analogous Debates",
          "timestamp": "15:38"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Further Clarification: When We Do and Do Not Combine Stringencies from Different Sides",
      "display_title": "When Combine Chumrot",
      "timestamp": "18:28",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The position of Rav Yehuda: all three stringencies are adopted in practice, though some dispute whether this is truly the ruling",
          "display_title": "Rav Yehuda's Practice",
          "timestamp": "18:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "Distinction: we do not combine chumrot when they contradict each other (mutually exclusive)",
          "display_title": "Mutually Contradictory",
          "timestamp": "19:31"
        },
        {
          "title": "Example of spine (shidra) and skull (gulgoles): Beit Shammai and Beit Hillel debate minimum sizes for impurity, with positions that reverse between tumah and tereifa contexts",
          "display_title": "Spine/Skull Example",
          "timestamp": "19:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "Explanation of how adopting both stringencies in the spine case would contradict itself across different halakhic contexts",
          "display_title": "Contradiction Illustrated",
          "timestamp": "21:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "The mavoi akum case revisited: Rav and Shmuel's positions are logically independent and do not contradict, so combining them is permissible",
          "display_title": "Mavoi Akum Revisited",
          "timestamp": "23:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "Case of Rabbi Akiva and the etrog: when one does not know which position to follow, combining chumrot out of doubt is permitted",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Akiva's Etrog",
          "timestamp": "25:55"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Practical Resolution: When Tzurat Hapetach Suffices and the Key Case of Alleyways Not Opening into Reshus Harabim on Both Ends",
      "display_title": "Practical Resolution",
      "timestamp": "29:46",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Summary of digression: stringencies debate and conclusion that we do apply them when logically independent",
          "display_title": "Summary",
          "timestamp": "29:46"
        },
        {
          "title": "The pivotal statement of Rav Yehuda in the name of Rav: the debate over tzurat hapetach versus door applies only when both ends open into reshus harabim",
          "display_title": "Rav's Key Point",
          "timestamp": "31:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "If one end opens into reshus harabim and the other into a valley or private area, tzurat hapetach suffices on one side; lechi and korah on the other",
          "display_title": "Mixed Openings",
          "timestamp": "32:25"
        },
        {
          "title": "If both ends open into valleys (not reshus harabim), only tzurat hapetach is needed; this is the basis for modern eruv practices",
          "display_title": "Valley Case",
          "timestamp": "33:04"
        },
        {
          "title": "Final coda attributed to Rav Yehuda (possibly from Shmuel): if an alleyway opens into a walled courtyard, nothing is required at that end",
          "display_title": "Courtyard Case",
          "timestamp": "34:59"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Abaye's Challenge and the Resolution via Rav Sheshet: Distinguishing Wall Requirements from Eruv Requirements",
      "display_title": "Abaye Challenge",
      "timestamp": "37:11",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Abaye identifies the courtyard case as Shmuel's position, not Rav's, based on a contradictory statement from Rav",
          "display_title": "Attribution Correction",
          "timestamp": "37:11"
        },
        {
          "title": "Citation of Rav's position via Rav Yirmiyah bar Abba: a mavoi opening fully into a courtyard where the courtyard opens into reshus harabim",
          "display_title": "Rav's Parallel Case",
          "timestamp": "37:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "In Rav's case: the courtyard is permitted but the mavoi is forbidden—explanation offered as a lack of eruv between mavoi and courtyard residents",
          "display_title": "Rav's Case Explained",
          "timestamp": "38:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Abaye's reasoning about why the mavoi is forbidden versus the courtyard permitted based on perspective and inclusion",
          "display_title": "Perspective Difference",
          "timestamp": "39:52"
        },
        {
          "title": "Response: Rav Yosef does not know the full reasoning but recounts a precedent from Rav Yehuda that the courtyard case requires nothing",
          "display_title": "Precedent Cited",
          "timestamp": "41:06"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Sheshet's explanation: the apparent contradiction between Rav's cases resolves by distinguishing wall requirements from eruv requirements",
          "display_title": "Rav Sheshet's Resolution",
          "timestamp": "43:43"
        },
        {
          "title": "The key insight: in the courtyard case, walls are sufficient, but the mavoi is forbidden not due to walls but due to lack of eruv joining mavoi and courtyard residents",
          "display_title": "Walls vs Eruv",
          "timestamp": "44:00"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Transition to Three-Walled Alleyway (Mavoi Asui Knadli) and the Debate Between Rav and Shmuel",
      "display_title": "Three-Walled Alley",
      "timestamp": "45:15",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Introduction to new case: mavoi with three walls and one open side",
          "display_title": "Three-Wall Case",
          "timestamp": "45:15"
        },
        {
          "title": "Debate stated: Rav says no lechi or korah needed on the fourth side; Shmuel says one is required",
          "display_title": "Rav vs Shmuel",
          "timestamp": "45:24"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
